File: A lightbulb. Pixabay/jplenio JOHANNESBURG - After being riddled with delays, the first three projects under the Risk Mitigation Independent Power Producer Procurement Programme have been finalised. Renewable energy developer, Scatec, can start constructing its hybrid solar and storage projects to provide emergency power to the country. READ: South Africans worry about debt, inflation, running out of money The projects are located in the Northern Cape and will provide 150 megawatts of on-demand power over a 20-year period. Scatec will own 51% of the equity in the project. Its black economic empowerment partner, H1 Holdings, owns 49%. South Africa is getting a step closer to solving it's energy crisis. After being riddled with delays, the first three projects under the Risk Mitigation Independent Power Producer Procurement Programme have been finalised. #DStv403 #eNCA pic.twitter.com/C9QinkHGtx